&gt; Subject: Re: RE: [junit] JUnit not matching to my needs - execute order
&gt; shows design flaw ?
&gt; 
&gt; By explicitly stating this is an assumption and that is a corollary
&gt; means that xUnit can better inform developers about where the true
&gt; problems exist in your application.
&gt; 
&gt; For instance, perhaps you are testing your database.  It is more more
&gt; informative for the CanConnectToDatabase test to fail because of
&gt; errors, as subsequent tests (like RetrieveData, SaveData, etc) to fail
&gt; because of an invalid assumption.
&gt; 
&gt; I picture things like additional colours for assumptions and
&gt; corollaries (lets say orange) in the xUnit gui.
&gt; 
&gt; andrew f
&gt; 
&gt; On Fri, 9 Jul 2004 11:26:47 -0400, David Plass &lt;dplass@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; How does adding &#39;assumptions&#39; and &#39;corollaries&#39; help? They&#39;re just
&gt; asserts,
&gt; &gt; after all, right?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; You can just have a more explicit message in the assert, e.g.,
&gt; &gt;    1) Assumption.AreEqual(3,list.Count,&quot;Check the count, and the add
&gt; &gt; methods&quot;);
&gt; &gt; becomes:
&gt; &gt;    assertEquals(&quot;Assumed the counts are equal&quot;, 3, list.Count);
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; 2) Corollory.IsTrue(list.ContainsOnly(typeof(string)));
&gt; &gt;    becomes
&gt; &gt;    assertTrue(&quot;Corollary: list only contains strings&quot;,
&gt; &gt; list.ContainsOnly(typeof(string)));
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Or did I miss completely your point?
&gt; &gt; --DP
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt; &gt; From: Andrew Forward [mailto:aforward@...]
&gt; &gt; Sent: Thursday, July 08, 2004 6:40 PM
&gt; &gt; To: junit@yahoogroups.com
&gt; &gt; Subject: Re: [junit] JUnit not matching to my needs - execute order shows
&gt; &gt; design flaw ?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Sometimes it is the case where a test is over-asserting itself, and
&gt; &gt; really checking for things that are already present in other tests (or
&gt; &gt; if not, then should be refactored into additional tests).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Let&#39;s look at a test for an array list (written in pseudo c#):
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; [Test]
&gt; &gt; public void GetElementAtMiddleIndex()
&gt; &gt; {
&gt; &gt;  ArrayList list = new ArrayList();
&gt; &gt;  list.Add(&quot;a&quot;);
&gt; &gt;  list.Add(&quot;b&quot;);
&gt; &gt;  list.Add(&quot;c&quot;);
&gt; &gt;  Assert.AreEqual(3,list.Count,&quot;the elements were not added properly);
&gt; &gt;  Assert.AreEqual(&quot;b&quot;,list[1]);
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Suppose that the indexing works fine, this test could still fail for
&gt; &gt; two reasons...
&gt; &gt;  1) The Add method is broken
&gt; &gt;  2) The Count property is broken
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; As is, the count is really not necessary.  We are not verifying Count
&gt; &gt; in this test, but rather indexing.  Although I would argue that it is
&gt; &gt; nice to have pre-requisites satisfied in the middle of a test, to help
&gt; &gt; direct your attention to the true cause of the issue.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Much like the snowball effect of the nuclear reactor plant example.  A
&gt; &gt; defect occurs, which in turn causes other defects (which in turn
&gt; &gt; causes more defects, and so on).  From an analysis perspective it is
&gt; &gt; difficult to pin-point the root defect because it is being masks but
&gt; &gt; subsequent ones.  Unlike the above example, where the order of the
&gt; &gt; defects can be used to unravel the issue, in testing order is
&gt; &gt; independent, so the primary defects are not necessarily those that
&gt; &gt; occur first.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; To address this, it would interesting to append two additional bits of
&gt; &gt; information on an assertion.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; 1) Assumption.AreEqual(3,list.Count,&quot;Check the count, and the add
&gt; methods&quot;);
&gt; &gt; 2) Corollory.IsTrue(list.ContainsOnly(typeof(string)));
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; An assumption is really a pre-requisite - that if fails, really means
&gt; &gt; that you were not even able to set-up to do the real testing.  Having
&gt; &gt; assumptions fail helps to pin-point coupling between components - as
&gt; &gt; well as helps direct your attention was secondary failing tests to the
&gt; &gt; primary ones (aka the failed Assertions).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; An corollary is something you believe to be true, but is not essential
&gt; &gt; to your unit test itself.  Corollaries are nice because you indirectly
&gt; &gt; add additional tests for other components of our system without that
&gt; &gt; much extra overhead.  Failing corollaries may highlight obscure bugs
&gt; &gt; in other parts of your system, or they highlight your
&gt; &gt; mis-understanding of those other parts (or they highlight a change to
&gt; &gt; the underlying assumptions of those parts).
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; On Thu, 8 Jul 2004 10:22:01 +0000, Jason Rogers
&gt; &gt; &lt;jacaetevha@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; On Wednesday 07 July 2004 10:49 pm, Curt Sampson wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  On Tue, 6 Jul 2004, hedgi wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   Now I there is the problem. I want to run &quot;testCommon&quot; first
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   which is in the &quot;BasicGetListTest&quot; but when I subclass it with
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   &quot;GlucoseGetListTest&quot; it is always executed last. I read some of
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   the postings in this newsgroup, but it seems that such kind of
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   requirement point a desing flaw and I should somehow rearrange my
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   Unit Test Structure to made the tests indepentdant. I&#39;m stuck
&gt; with
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  &gt;   it.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  I&#39;ve been thinking for a while that this is a serious problem in
&gt; JUnit
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  (and most unit testing frameworks), because it&#39;s been such an
&gt; annoyance
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  for so many people. Let&#39;s face it; a lot of groups of tests do have
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  known dependencies between tests such that if test A fails, we know
&gt; &gt; that
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  the output of tests B, C and D are uninteresting. Yet we end up
&gt; running
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  B, C and D anyway, and then searching through all the error output
&gt; for
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  the failure that we know is the &quot;real&quot; one, ignoring all the others
&gt; as
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;  spurious.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; With all due respect, I believe that is a code smell.  It seems to say
&gt; to
&gt; &gt; me
&gt; &gt; &gt; that there is something not right about the design of the code being
&gt; &gt; tested,
&gt; &gt; &gt; or perhaps even more elusive, something is wrong with how the tests are
&gt; &gt; &gt; written.  When I find these types of dependencies I inevitably rethink
&gt; how
&gt; &gt; I
&gt; &gt; &gt; have written my tests.  Have I coded in the dependencies or are they
&gt; &gt; really
&gt; &gt; &gt; there.  More times than not I have coded in the dependencies -- and
&gt; &gt; therefore
&gt; &gt; &gt; I can remove them.  Further, I would argue that I _NEED_ to remove them.
&gt; &gt; &gt; Now, maybe I am old-fashioned but I believe tests (at least at the
&gt; &gt; &gt; unit/programmer level) ought to be as autonomous as possible.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; --
